Subsetting

set.seed(6174)
samp <- rnorm(n = 100, mean = 50, sd = 15)
length(which(samp < 65 & samp > 35)) # % within 1 sd
## [1] 62
length(which(samp < 80 & samp > 20)) # % within 2 sd
## [1] 98
length(which(samp < 95 & samp > 5)) # % within 3 sd
## [1] 99

In my random sample of 100 from a mean of 50 and standard deviation of 15, 63% were within 1 standard deviation, 98% were within 2 standard deviations, and 99% were within 3 standard deviations. It was expected that the data would respectively fall between 68%, 95%, and 99.7%.

6.5 and 6.6

FtoC <- function(f) {
  cel <- (f-32)*(5/9)
  return(cel)
}
FtoC(100)
## [1] 37.77778
FtoK <- function(f) {
  cel <- FtoC(f)
  kel <- cel + 273
  return(kel)
}
FtoK(100)
## [1] 310.7778

Plotting

\[p_{t+1} = \frac{p^2w_{AA} + pqw_{AB}}{p_t^2w_{AA} + 2pqw_{AB} + q^2w_{BB}}\]

sel <- function(p, wAA, wAB, wBB) {
  q <- 1 - p
  wbar <- (p^2)*wAA + 2*p*q*wAB + (q^2)*wBB
  pt1 <- ((p^2)*wAA + p*q*wAB)/wbar
  return(pt1)
}
pt <- seq(from = 0, to = 1, by = 0.01)
pt1 <- sel(p = pt, wAA = 1, wAB = 1, wBB = 0.5)
plot(x = pt, y = pt1, las = 1)
